data.content:
## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a worker that exceeds a deadline, catches `ThreadAbortException`, and calls `Thread.ResetAbort()`. All three APIs throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` or are obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`) in .NET 6+.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Block until the task completes or the timeout fires.
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout.
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(() => work(), token)` | Tasks use the thread pool; avoids manual thread lifecycle |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult()` | `WaitAsync` (.NET 6+) respects the cancellation token |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation replaces forcible abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No equivalent needed — cancellation is cooperative |

### ⚠️ Critical Pitfall

**The work delegate `Func<T>` doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, so cancellation cannot reach inside it.** The timeout only stops *waiting* — the work itself may continue running on a thread-pool thread until it finishes naturally.

This is the fundamental difference: `Thread.Abort` forcibly killed the thread; cooperative cancellation requires the work to *opt in*.

**If you control the work**, pass the token through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — work checks the token at regular intervals:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Other pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Forgetting `using` on CancellationTokenSource** | Leaks internal timers. Always dispose it. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use the `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter to distinguish your timeout from unrelated cancellations. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If the work calls a library you can't modify and it ignores the token, the only true "kill" mechanism is `Process.Kill` on a child process. |
| **Assuming instant cancellation** | Cancellation only fires at the next `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` call or token-aware API. Long gaps between checks = delayed cancellation. |
